Roman like Greek Comedy may be traced back to the Harvest, Vintage and other Festivals. ‘The joy of harvest' found expression in alternate verses, singer answering singer‚ at first playful, but gradually becoming so personal and bitter as finally to call for the inter- ference of the law. Hence sprang the uersus Fescennz‘m' which

are said to derive their name from the South Etrurian town Fescennium. Their metre was the Saturnian, the one national

Roman product in matters rhythmical, a mixture of the iambic and trochaic rhythm. The Italian habit of rivals improvising verses always has been, and still is, a favourite entertainment among Italian rustics.

A pestilence at Rome in the consulship of C. Sulpicius Paeticus and C. Licinius Stolo B.C. 364 led to the invitation of Etruscan players (ludiones), who introduced the mimic dance without words but with flute—accompaniment.
